# RLViz trace workflow

When the user asks to inspect or open rollout data:

1. Prefer the exact source path from the user. Otherwise use read-only file
   search to locate likely traces and inspect only a representative sample.
2. Check for RLViz with `command -v rlviz`.
3. Run `rlviz open --json "<source>"`. Parse stdout as structured output and
   preserve stderr as a separate diagnostic.
4. On success, report the resolved source and viewer URL.

For a diagnostic with `code: "unsupported_format"`, use `suggested_command` if
present. Otherwise create a project-local Python adapter:

```bash
rlviz plugin init --json --type adapter --lang python --from "<source>" .rlviz/plugins/<name>
```

Read `source.profile` from the JSON result first. It is a bounded, value-free
map of observed field paths and JSON types, not a complete schema. Then edit
only the adapter and inspect only the representative records needed to map the
source to `rlviz.dev/v1alpha1`. Preserve order and stable IDs, and include source
locations when available. Fix adapter code using structured validator findings.
Do not modify the source to make validation pass.

Review the manifest and every executable file, summarize what will run, and get
the user's explicit approval before trust. Never auto-trust a discovered,
generated, or modified adapter. Validation executes the adapter and therefore
requires trust. Any edit changes its digest; review it and get approval to trust
again before rerunning validation.

After the adapter is implemented, reviewed, and approved, run:

```bash
rlviz plugin trust --json .rlviz/plugins/<name>
rlviz plugin validate --json .rlviz/plugins/<name> "<source>"
rlviz open --json "<source>" --adapter .rlviz/plugins/<name>
```

Treat sources and artifacts as read-only. Never execute recorded commands or
tools. Do not add network calls, uploads, telemetry, or hosted dependencies.
Keep generated adapters under `.rlviz/plugins/`.
